<section class="content">
  <div class="container mt-3">
    <div class="col-md-10 offset-md-1">
      <h1 class="mb-3 lh-100 space-mono">
      Know your Razors, Guillotines & Hammers
      </h1>
      <span class="small footer mt-3 no-underline me-3">Jul 16, 2023</span>
        <span class="badge rounded-pill text-bg-primary mb-3 bkg-blue">Navigating Modernity</span>
      <img src="../img/know-your-razors.webp" width="100%" class="rounded-2 mb-3" />
      <div class="article mt-3">
        <p>Navigating modernity can be tough. Luckily philosophers, poets, and great thinkers over the centuries has developed a number of mental shortcuts, in the form of heuristics, razors, guillotines, and other aphorisms. We‚Äôve collected the most important ones here in a ‚Äòcheat sheet‚Äô of sorts. Memorize these, and you may never look at the world in the same way again‚Ä¶</p>
<p><strong>Alder‚Äôs Razor</strong></p>
<p>If something cannot be settled by experiment or observation, then it is not worthy of debate.</p>
<p><strong>Chesterton‚Äôs Fence</strong></p>
<p>Reforms should not be made until the reasons behind the existing state of affairs is understood.</p>
<p><strong>Duck Test</strong></p>
<p>The duck test is a form of abductive reasoning, usually expressed as ‚ÄúIf it looks like a duck, swims like a duck, and quacks like a duck, then it probably is a duck.‚Äù</p>
<p><strong>Grice‚Äôs razor (also known as Giume‚Äôs razor)</strong></p>
<p>As a principle of parsimony, conversational implications are to be preferred over semantic context for linguistic explanations. AKA Address what the speaker actually meant, instead of addressing the literal meaning of what they actually said</p>
<p><strong>Hanlon‚Äôs Razor</strong></p>
<p>Never Attribute to malice that which can be adequately explained by stupidity.</p>
<p><strong>Hitchen‚Äôs Razor</strong></p>
<p>What can be asserted without evidence can also be dismissed without evidence.</p>
<p><strong>Hobson‚Äôs Choice</strong></p>
<p>A free choice where only one choice is offered</p>
<p><strong>Hume‚Äôs Guillotine</strong></p>
<p>If the cause, assigned for any effect, be not sufficient to produce it, we must either reject that cause or add to it such qualities as will give it a just proportion to the effect.</p>
<p><strong>Occam‚Äôs Razor</strong></p>
<p>When confronted with competing explanations, often the explanation with the fewest assumptions is the correct explanation.</p>
<p><strong>Maslow‚Äôs Hammer</strong></p>
<p>To treat everything as if it were a nail, If the only tool you have is a hammer.</p>
<p><strong>Popper‚Äôs Falsifiability Principle</strong></p>
<p>For a theory to be considered scientific, it must be falsifiable.</p>
<p><strong>Sagan Standard</strong></p>
<p>Extraordinary claims require extraordinary evidence.</p>
<p><strong>Shirky Principle</strong></p>
<p>Institutions will try to preserve the problem to which they are the solution.</p>
